/.worktrees/performance-logging-investigation\",\"sessionId\":\"2d62938d-a5d3-4bac-9d0f-bf8056720e6d\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"performance-logging-investigation\",\"slug\":\"wiggly-weaving-crayon\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"PostToolUse\",\"hookName\":\"PostToolUse:Agent\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code post-task\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01Fx78q7HjzgFctguZnZVm2M\",\"toolUseID\":\"toolu_01Fx78q7HjzgFctguZnZVm2M\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T22:42:30.686Z\",\"uuid\":\"452fc8b6-edc4-4b44-aae3-f03c0cb2e54c\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"284484a5-2b66-44a9-b2fd-7c62ddd56621\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/.worktrees/performance-logging-investigation\",\"sessionId\":\"2d62938d-a5d3-4bac-9d0f-bf8056720e6d\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"performance-logging-investigation\",\"slug\":\"wiggly-weaving-crayon\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01Fx78q7HjzgFctguZnZVm2M\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Now I have a thorough understanding of the implementation, plan, and surrounding code. Here is my review.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Code Review: `perf/` Package (Tasks 1-3)\\n\\n### Summary\\n\\nThe implementation covers Tasks 1-3 from the plan: `context.go`, `span.go`, and `span_test.go`. The code is well-structured, faithful to the plan, and all 8 tests pass. The API is clean and the package has the right dependency footprint (stdlib + `logging` only). Below is a detailed assessment.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Plan Alignment\\n\\n**Faithful to plan:** The implementation matches the plan specification almost exactly across all three files. The data structures, function signatures, and test cases are a near-verbatim match to what the plan prescribed.\\n\\n**One intentional improvement in `Measure()`:** The plan specified:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc (s *Span) Measure(name string, fn func()) {\\n    _, child := Start(s.ctx, name)\\n    fn()\\n    child.End()\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe implementation at `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/.worktrees/performance-logging-investigation/perf/span.go` lines 82-87 adds an explicit `contextWithSpan(s.ctx, s)` call before `Start()`:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc (s *Span) Measure(name string, fn func()) {\\n    ctx := contextWithSpan(s.ctx, s)\\n    _, child := Start(ctx, name)\\n    fn()\\n    child.End()\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis is a **correct and necessary deviation** from the plan. Without it, if `Measure()` is called on a span whose stored `s.ctx` does not already have `s` as the current span (e.g., if the span was created as a child but the caller reuses the parent context), `Start()` would attach the child to the wrong parent. Wrapping with `contextWithSpan(s.ctx, s)` ensures the new child always attaches to `s`.\\n\\n**Commit structure deviation:** The plan specified three separate commits (one per task). The actual implementation was done in a single commit (`5818a28d`). This is a minor workflow deviation with no impact on code quality.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Code Quality Assessment\\n\\n#### What was done well\\n\\n1. **Clean separation of concerns.** `context.go` handles context plumbing only; `span.go` handles the Span lifecycle and logging. This follows the same pattern as `cmd/entire/cli/logging/context.go`.\\n\\n2. **Idempotent `End()`.** The `ended` guard at line 45-47 of `span.go` prevents double-counting and double-logging, which is essential when using `defer span.End()` alongside explicit `End()` calls.\\n\\n3. **Auto-end of children.** Lines 63-68 of `span.go` ensure that forgotten child spans still get duration values recorded, preventing silent data loss.\\n\\n4. **All fields are unexported.** The `Span` struct at lines 13-22 of `span.go` correctly keeps all fields private, forcing callers through the public API. This preserves the ability to change internals without breaking consumers.\\n\\n5. **Tests are parallel.** Every test function calls `t.Parallel()`, consistent with the project's CLAUDE.md requirements.\\n\\n6. **Good test coverage.** The tests cover: root span creation, nesting, duration recording, idempotent End, auto-end of children, Measure helper, empty context, and multiple children.\\n\\n#### Issues\\n\\n**Important -- Thread safety of Span fields**\\n\\nThe `Span` struct is not safe for concurrent access. The `children` slice (line 16 of `span.go`) is mutated by `append` in `Start()` (line 36), while `End()` iterates over `children` (line 63). If two goroutines call `Start()` with the same parent context simultaneously, there will be a data race on the `children` slice.\\n\\nFor the currently planned usage (sequential hook instrumentation within a single goroutine), this is acceptable. However, the design doc states \\\"Future instrumentation of new operations requires only adding `perf.Start()`/`span.End()` calls -- no framework changes.\\\" If a future caller uses spans across goroutines (e.g., parallel substeps), this will produce data races.\\n\\n**Recommendation:** Add a comment on the `Span` struct documenting that it is not safe for concurrent use. This makes the constraint explicit without adding unnecessary locking overhead:\\n\\n```go\\n// Span tracks timing for an operation and its substeps.\\n// A Span is not safe for concurrent use from multiple goroutines.\\ntype Span struct {\\n```\\n\\n**Important -- `component` attribute may conflict with logging context**\\n\\nIn `span.go` line 58, the `End()` method hardcodes `slog.String(\\\"component\\\", \\\"perf\\\")`. Looking at `cmd/entire/cli/logging/logger.go` lines 329-334, the `attrsFromContext` function already extracts a `component` value from context and appends it to log attributes. If the context passed to `Start()` already has a component set via `logging.WithComponent()`, the emitted log line will contain **two** `component` keys -- one from context extraction (`\\\"hooks\\\"` or similar) and one from the span (`\\\"perf\\\"`).\\n\\nJSON slog output handles duplicate keys by including both, which means log parsers could pick up either value depending on implementation. This is not a correctness bug, but it produces confusing log output.\\n\\n**Recommendation:** Either:\\n- (a) Remove the hardcoded `slog.String(\\\"component\\\", \\\"perf\\\")` from span output and rely on the caller setting the context component, or\\n- (b) Document that perf spans intentionally override the component to `\\\"perf\\\"` for easy filtering, and consider if this is the desired behavior.\\n\\nGiven that the design doc says the output should be filterable by `\\\"component\\\": \\\"perf\\\"`, option (b) seems intentional. A brief code comment would clarify this.\\n\\n**Suggestion -- Capacity preallocation off by potential amount**\\n\\nAt `span.go` line 57:\\n\\n```go\\nattrs := make([]any, 0, 3+len(s.children)+len(s.attrs))\\n```\\n\\nThe capacity `3 + len(s.children) + len(s.attrs)` is correct for the current implementation. This is fine as-is; just noting it is tightly coupled to the exact number of hardcoded attributes (component, op, duration_ms = 3).\\n\\n**Suggestion -- Deeply nested spans only log one level**\\n\\nThe `End()` method on lines 63-71 only iterates over direct `children`. If there are grandchildren (spans nested 3+ deep), their timings are not included in the log output. The flat `steps.<name>_ms` keys design intentionally does this (per the design doc: \\\"Flat `steps.<name>_ms` keys (not nested objects)\\\"), but it means deeply nested span trees silently lose timing data.\\n\\nFor the planned instrumentation (root span per hook, one level of substeps), this is sufficient. If deeper nesting is ever used, a recursive flattening approach (e.g., `steps.parent.child_ms`) would capture the full tree. No action needed now -- just worth noting for future instrumentation tasks.\\n\\n**Suggestion -- Test for log output content**\\n\\nThe plan's Task 3 description mentions: \\\"Tests verify: ... log output format. The tests use a similar pattern to `cmd/entire/cli/logging/logger_test.go` -- writing to a buffer via the logging package then parsing JSON.\\\"\\n\\nThe actual tests do not verify log output. They test span structure and duration but never assert on the log line content (the `component`, `op`, `duration_ms`, or `steps.*_ms` keys). This is a gap between the plan and implementation.\\n\\nThis is a lower priority since the logging integration is tested indirectly (root span `End()` calls `logging.Debug()` which is well-tested separately), but a test that captures the actual log output and verifies the expected keys would catch regressions in the output format.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Architecture and Design\\n\\nThe package placement at `perf/` (top-level module package) is appropriate. It avoids the deep nesting of `cmd/entire/cli/` and keeps the dependency direction clean: `perf` depends on `logging`, and future hook/strategy code will depend on `perf`. No circular dependency risk.\\n\\nThe context propagation pattern matches the established idiom in the codebase (`logging/context.go`). The use of an unexported `contextKey` struct prevents key collisions across packages.\\n\\nThe single-responsibility design is sound: `perf` only measures and logs timing. It does not try to be a tracing framework, metrics system, or configuration system. This aligns well with the \\\"Alternatives Considered\\\" section of the design doc.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Final Summary\\n\\n| Category | Rating | Notes |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Plan alignment | Strong | Near-exact match; one justified `Measure()` improvement |\\n| Code correctness | Strong | All tests pass; API is clean and idempotent |\\n| Code quality | Good | Well-structured, follows project conventions |\\n| Test coverage | Good | 8 tests covering core behavior; log output verification missing |\\n| Thread safety | Documented gap | Not concurrent-safe; acceptable for planned use, needs comment |\\n| Architecture | Strong | Clean dependency direction, appropriate package placement |\\n\\n**Action items:**\\n\\n1. **(Important)** Add a concurrency safety comment on the `Span` struct in `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/.worktrees/performance-logging-investigation/perf/span.go` line 13.\\n2. **(Important)** Add a comment on the `component` attribute override at `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/.worktrees/performance-logging-investigation/perf/span.go` line 58 to clarify the intentional duplicate key behavior.\\n3. **(Suggestion)** Consider adding a log output integration test that captures the DEBUG output and verifies the expected JSON keys, as described in the plan's Task 3 description.\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"agentId: a063b227087435b38 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\\n<usage>total_tokens: 55099\\ntool_uses: 17\\nduration_ms: 92224</usage>\"}]}]},\"uuid\":\"34160505-e8df-48e8-b24c-3d2042246e10\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T22:42:30.685Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"prompt\":\"Review the perf package implementation for code quality.\\n\\nWHAT_WAS_IMPLEMENTED: New `perf/` package with span-based performance measurement API (context.go, span.go, span_test.go)\\nPLAN_OR_REQUIREMENTS: Task 1-3 from docs/plans/2026-03-03-perf-framework-plan.md\\nBASE_SHA: 256ba8bb\\nHEAD_SHA: 5818a28d\\nDESCRIPTION: Lightweight span-based timing framework for hook instrumentation. Core API: Start/End/Measure with context-propagated nesting. Root spans emit single DEBUG log line via logging.Debug().\\n\\nWork from: /Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/.worktrees/performance-logging-investigation\",\"agentId\":\"a063b227087435b38\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Now I have a thorough understanding of the implementation, plan, and surrounding code. Here is my review.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Code Review: `perf/` Package (Tasks 1-3)\\n\\n### Summary\\n\\nThe implementation covers Tasks 1-3 from the plan: `context.go